<dl id="n56118b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56118b">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56118b"> 118(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Maramara ~ <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56118b"><li>FW 595.27 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/lexta.htm#n56118b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/l39ta.htm#n56118b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56118b">MS BL 47488.45v</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:070 <a name="tad4" href="../../ff/fdra/tda.htm#tad4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ta/tad4.htm#n56118b">Draft: IV&sect;1.4</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: New Ireland: In New Britain/New Ireland, as among all Papuan races in the same stage of development, descent is always reckoned through the mother. Every man and woman from date of birth belongs to one of two classes, called respectively <i>Pikalaba</i> and <i>Maramara</i> and as descent is reckoned through the mother, it necessarily follows that the children of every <i>Pikalaba</i> woman are also all <i>Pikalaba</i>, both male and female, and vice versa. All lands, fruit-brearting trees, fishing-stones, etc., are also all included in one or other of these divisions. No <i>Pikalaba</i> or <i>Maramara</i> man can marry a woman of the same class as himself: this would be regarded as incest, irrespectively. </mm> </dd></dl>
